docs.abstract: On his first campaign stop for the Martin Luther King holiday in South Carolina, Joe Biden denounced the president in some of his strongest language yet.
docs.snippet: On his first campaign stop for the Martin Luther King holiday in South Carolina, Joe Biden denounced the president in some of his strongest language yet.
docs.lead_paragraph: COLUMBIA, S.C. — Former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr. paid a visit to Sunday services at Bethlehem Baptist Church, a large black congregation here, urging the crowd to fight back against hatred and condemning President Trump in some of his strongest language yet for heightening racial divisions in the country.

headline.main: Mentioning Trump and K.K.K. in Same Sentence, Biden Condemns Hate
headline.print_headline: Naming Trump and Klan In the Same Sentence, Biden Condemns Hate

docs.abstract: The aide reportedly offered campaign contributions to Iowa candidates who endorsed Mr. Steyer.
docs.snippet: The aide reportedly offered campaign contributions to Iowa candidates who endorsed Mr. Steyer.
docs.lead_paragraph: Tom Steyer’s presidential campaign apologized on Thursday for “any miscommunication” it might have conveyed following a report that a top aide had privately offered campaign contributions to local candidates who would endorse Mr. Steyer.

headline.main: Tom Steyer Aide Apologizes for ‘Miscommunication’ on Endorsement Solicitation

docs.abstract: While demanding that an opponent, Pete Buttigieg, disclose his McKinsey clients, Ms. Warren provided a fuller explanation of her compensation as a legal consultant.
docs.snippet: While demanding that an opponent, Pete Buttigieg, disclose his McKinsey clients, Ms. Warren provided a fuller explanation of her compensation as a legal consultant.
docs.lead_paragraph: Senator Elizabeth Warren disclosed a detailed list of compensation she received during 30 years of moonlighting as a legal consultant — about $1.9 million in all — as she and Mayor Pete Buttigieg continued a back-and-forth demanding transparency in the race for the Democratic presidential nomination.

headline.main: Elizabeth Warren Earned $1.9 Million Over 3 Decades for Corporate and Legal Work
headline.print_headline: Warren Discloses $1.9 Million in Earnings as Consultant

docs.abstract: With impeachment behind the president, his re-election campaign wants to address political weaknesses exacerbated by his policies and behavior.
docs.snippet: With impeachment behind the president, his re-election campaign wants to address political weaknesses exacerbated by his policies and behavior.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Buoyed by his impeachment acquittal and the muddled Democratic primary race, President Trump and his campaign are turning to address his re-election bid’s greatest weaknesses with an aggressive, well-funded but uncertain effort to win back suburban voters turned off by his policies and behavior.

headline.main: On Trump’s To-Do List: Take Back The Suburbs. Court Black Voters. Expand the Electoral Map. Win.
headline.print_headline: President’s Team Aims to Win Back Suburban Voters

byline.original: By Maggie Haberman, Annie Karni and Jonathan Martin

docs.abstract: For months, the two candidates had rarely faced off in direct attacks. But now, as the polling leaders, they are using the other as a foil to press their divergent cases for the presidency.
docs.snippet: For months, the two candidates had rarely faced off in direct attacks. But now, as the polling leaders, they are using the other as a foil to press their divergent cases for the presidency.
docs.lead_paragraph: SALEM, N.H. — Bernie Sanders stands before his audience reciting his familiar pitch, railing against the elite and declaring that America is “the only major country not to guarantee health care for all.” He directs his message to working-class voters and young people, vowing to make it easier to join unions and to legalize marijuana across the country. He is holding concerts to show off his big crowds.

headline.main: Sanders and Buttigieg Close Out New Hampshire Pitching Different Visions
headline.print_headline: Sanders and Buttigieg Ramp Up Rivalry as They Prepare for a Primary Showdown

byline.original: By Sydney Ember and Nick Corasaniti

docs.abstract: Iowa caucusgoers aren’t just asking about the one issue that’s dominating the headlines.
docs.snippet: Iowa caucusgoers aren’t just asking about the one issue that’s dominating the headlines.
docs.lead_paragraph: MARSHALLTOWN, Iowa — With three jurors in the impeachment trial traipsing about Iowa this past weekend, you’d expect someone — anyone! — planning to attend the Iowa caucuses to ask the presidential candidates about impeachment.

docs.abstract: The candidates gave their stump speeches. They took photos and shook hands. They tried mightily to address the polling elephant in the room without appearing to concern themselves with it.
docs.snippet: The candidates gave their stump speeches. They took photos and shook hands. They tried mightily to address the polling elephant in the room without appearing to concern themselves with it.
docs.lead_paragraph: DES MOINES — With the Iowa caucuses a week away and senators briefly sprung from their impeachment-induced confinement on Capitol Hill, the Democratic presidential candidates and their surrogates spilled out across Iowa on Sunday.

headline.main: T Minus 8 Days: A Frenetic Weekend on the Trail in Iowa
headline.print_headline: Frenetic Weekend for Democrats as Iowa Campaign Enters the Home Stretch

docs.abstract: Elizabeth Warren, Pete Buttigieg and Amy Klobuchar are trying to knock each other out in the Iowa caucuses, where they need strong finishes to stay viable in the 2020 race.
docs.snippet: Elizabeth Warren, Pete Buttigieg and Amy Klobuchar are trying to knock each other out in the Iowa caucuses, where they need strong finishes to stay viable in the 2020 race.
docs.lead_paragraph: DES MOINES — As Elizabeth Warren and Amy Klobuchar escalated their attacks on Pete Buttigieg in Thursday night’s Democratic debate, and Mr. Buttigieg forcefully pushed back, a crucial if unspoken fact was driving the political combat: All three candidates are trying to knock each other out in the Iowa caucuses, where they need strong finishes to stay viable in the 2020 race.

headline.main: Democratic Debate Clashes Had a Common Denominator: Iowa
headline.print_headline: Clashes on Debate Stage Mirror Battle to Win Big in Iowa

byline.original: By Sydney Ember and Reid J. Epstein

docs.abstract: Ranking first is still the best, of course. But in the Iowa caucuses, second-choice candidates can win.
docs.snippet: Ranking first is still the best, of course. But in the Iowa caucuses, second-choice candidates can win.
docs.lead_paragraph: The snow was starting to come down. Senator Amy Klobuchar was snapping selfies at a campaign event. And Monica Peitz and Peg Raney, two friends from central Iowa, were discussing the question that it seemed every Democrat in the state was asking: Who is on your list?

headline.main: Why Candidates Want to Be Iowans’ Second Choice
